		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Kaeaelin wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV>Everything no drop is an interesting concept, I've wondered how this game would pan out in that scenario. It would obviously, but a major dent in a plat farmers ability to leech income from Sony's game.<BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>Thats essentially how the EQ2 economy works. Not that everything is NODROP but everything is attunable. There is no "used" gear on the market, only new drops or crafted items. It tends to prevent the cost of items to fall over time and there is actually a pretty stable economy with crafters able to maek money at all level ranges as long as there are players needing gear inthat level range. Gear is also very level specific with a new "tier" of gear available every 10 levels. Sure you can continue to use your level 20 armor quest armors when youa re level 40 but it will not be nearly as usefull as even common dropped items by then. There is very little twinking (other then spell upgrades and rare crafted armor).</P>
<P>There is also almost no camping and definitely no KSing. A lot of the mechanics of EQ2 are very nice. Most hard core EQ players don't like&nbsp;EQ2 though&nbsp;becasue it is a lot easier to play then old school EQ as I am remebering by playing on the progressions servers!</P>	
