		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			As a casual, mostly non-raiding, time-restricted player, I hate the idea of a time-restricted server. I still like the idea that was posted on another thread like this that I clarified. The only downside I see to this is the investment in hardware required by SoE. What do y'all think about this:<br><br><blockquote><hr>Mayera wrote:<br>One of the best ideas I've seen was early on in this thread: A progression of progression servers. First off, use the setup of the current progression servers. It's not a true &quot;old school&quot; server, just limited content.<br><br>Server 1 launches: Players can unlock old planes, kunark, velious. Once velious is completed (requirements met to unlock Luclin), server 2 launches. Free one-way character moves (or copies) allowed to Server 2.<br><br>Server 2: Old world, Kunark, Velious, and Luclin unlocked at launch. Players can unlock PoP, ldon, Loy, maybe GoD. Once GoD or Omens is unlocked server 3 launches. Free one-way character moves allowed to Server 3.<br><br>Server 3: All expansions up through GoD/Omens unlocked at launch. Players can unlock DoN, DoD, PoR...etc<br><br>This gets you two things:<br>1) The uber &quot;server firsts&quot; crowd can still do their thing and push content as fast as possible.<br><br>2) Once the ubers have unlocked everything on a server, they move on to the next, leaving the economy less ruined by mudflation on their source server.<br><br>3) The &quot;hardcore&quot; nostalgics can stay in the original trilogy as long as they want. If they do finally get bored and decide to give the other expansions a whirl, they move to Server 2, and they're only 3 or so expansions behind the &quot;top end&quot; of that server. They have a chance to be at least somewhat close to &quot;on par&quot; with the average player on Server 2.<br><br>4) The occasional true newb that still floats into the game can start from Server 1 and work their way up, learning the game the only good way to learn it... starting from the beginning. They don't have to be PL'd or geared up just to have fun with their friends. It's the ultimate level playing field.<br><br>This system is the best implementation I can think of that makes both the &quot;rapid progression&quot; and &quot;nostalgia&quot; folks happy.<br><div></div><br><hr></blockquote>	
		</td></tr>
